{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/sickle-cell-disease/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-an-acute-sickle-cell-crisis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"68746f0d-607a-5db5-8949-a87a4ed29328","slug":"when-to-suspect-an-acute-sickle-cell-crisis","fullItemName":"When to suspect an acute sickle cell crisis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 58053a9c-af29-4570-923b-a6b60172f118 --><h2>When should I suspect an acute sickle cell crisis?</h2><!-- end field 58053a9c-af29-4570-923b-a6b60172f118 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item abb2e130-cde6-4eaa-817d-a6b60172eed4 --><!-- begin field 116fd768-ab40-4dff-a8a9-a6b60172f118 --><ul><li><strong>Suspect an <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sickle-cell-disease/background-information/complications/#acute-complications\">acute sickle cell crisis</a> in a person with sickle cell disease who presents with a sudden onset of pain, infection, anaemia, or other <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sickle-cell-disease/background-information/complications/#acute-complications\">symptoms</a>, such as a stroke or priapism. </strong><ul><li>There is often a history of a previous crisis (or rarely, sickle cell disease may be undiagnosed).</li><li>Older children and adults are often able to state whether their pain is typical of sickle cell disease.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 116fd768-ab40-4dff-a8a9-a6b60172f118 --><!-- end item abb2e130-cde6-4eaa-817d-a6b60172eed4 -->","topic":{"id":"eb346bd0-1df2-5db2-a583-a366e34cfc19","topicId":"cc107f5d-efe6-4625-840e-5c4d4656869b","topicName":"Sickle cell disease","slug":"sickle-cell-disease","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2016","chapters":[{"id":"d2b6d668-4d29-5c50-b65d-7467cbcce2dd","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"47f9af8d-8bda-55a3-bf81-eb75a7c4f02a","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i